WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.866 --> 00:00:03.740
SAURABH MADAAN: Hello,
and welcome, everyone.

00:00:03.740 --> 00:00:06.020
Today is a very, very
special event for us.

00:00:06.020 --> 00:00:09.920
We have two previous
Google author speakers

00:00:09.920 --> 00:00:12.960
and famous value
investors with us.

00:00:12.960 --> 00:00:16.520
Let me introduce one of
them first, to begin with.

00:00:16.520 --> 00:00:21.170
Mohnish Pabrai is the managing
partner of Pabrai Funds.

00:00:21.170 --> 00:00:23.820
He's also the
founder of Dakshana,

00:00:23.820 --> 00:00:26.670
a nonprofit organization,
which has sent hundreds

00:00:26.670 --> 00:00:30.610
of impoverished kids to the
IITs, which are the most

00:00:30.610 --> 00:00:34.550
sought-after colleges in India.

00:00:34.550 --> 00:00:36.520
We are very pleased to
have you again with us.

00:00:36.520 --> 00:00:37.620
So welcome, Mohnish.

00:00:37.620 --> 00:00:41.090
And let's start with a brief
introductory remarks from you.

00:00:41.090 --> 00:00:42.549
MOHNISH PABRAI: Thank you.

00:00:42.549 --> 00:00:43.340
Thank you, Saurabh.

00:00:43.340 --> 00:00:47.030
It's a pleasure to be here and
pleasure to be back at Google.

00:00:47.030 --> 00:00:49.840
And now I'm our shareholder.

00:00:49.840 --> 00:00:54.010
So last time I came I was not
appropriately portfolioed,

00:00:54.010 --> 00:00:55.520
but now I'm
shareholder of Google,

00:00:55.520 --> 00:01:02.870
so it's great to look at
what my money is doing.

00:01:02.870 --> 00:01:05.459
And I'm bullish on the
prospect, if you will.

00:01:05.459 --> 00:01:12.630
So just very quickly before we
get into Q&amp;A, like many of you,

00:01:12.630 --> 00:01:15.490
I'm an engineer.

00:01:15.490 --> 00:01:17.980
And I did my undergrad
in computer engineering.

00:01:17.980 --> 00:01:22.690
I actually never had looked
at the stock market or stocks

00:01:22.690 --> 00:01:24.530
or went to business school.

00:01:24.530 --> 00:01:28.760
And in 1994, quite
by accident, I

00:01:28.760 --> 00:01:32.930
read a book, which is the
one you can see on the slide.

00:01:32.930 --> 00:01:35.130
It's by Roger Lowenstein.

00:01:35.130 --> 00:01:37.600
And it's a biography on
Buffett-- "Buffett-- the Making

00:01:37.600 --> 00:01:39.240
of an American Capitalist."

00:01:39.240 --> 00:01:43.050
And I was very lucky
because just at that time

00:01:43.050 --> 00:01:47.200
the first couple of biographies
on Warren Buffett had come out.

00:01:47.200 --> 00:01:55.040
And when I read the book, it led
to a very significant epiphany,

00:01:55.040 --> 00:01:58.640
which eventually led me--
immediately, actually,

00:01:58.640 --> 00:02:01.880
almost immediately-- to start
spending something like about

00:02:01.880 --> 00:02:05.970
20 hours a week on
investment research,

00:02:05.970 --> 00:02:11.420
and then about five years
after that to actually do a 180

00:02:11.420 --> 00:02:15.140
and start an investment fund.

00:02:15.140 --> 00:02:21.620
And the thing that I found
very compelling about the book

00:02:21.620 --> 00:02:25.930
was that Warren has
this saying that I'm

00:02:25.930 --> 00:02:28.590
a better businessman
because I'm an investor,

00:02:28.590 --> 00:02:31.520
and I'm a better investor,
because I'm a businessman--

00:02:31.520 --> 00:02:33.780
interplay between
running a business

00:02:33.780 --> 00:02:36.920
and managing an
investment portfolio.

00:02:36.920 --> 00:02:40.620
And when I read
Buffett's biography

00:02:40.620 --> 00:02:44.730
it dawned on me
that the tools you

00:02:44.730 --> 00:02:49.730
use when you're
making investments

00:02:49.730 --> 00:02:52.109
are almost identical
to the tools you use

00:02:52.109 --> 00:02:53.400
when you're running a business.

00:02:53.400 --> 00:02:56.240
So for example, I
was at that time

00:02:56.240 --> 00:02:58.420
running an IT services company.

00:02:58.420 --> 00:03:02.280
And I would probably
spend maybe 2% or 3%

00:03:02.280 --> 00:03:05.530
of my time on strategy
and direction--

00:03:05.530 --> 00:03:09.010
figuring out which
areas we would focus on

00:03:09.010 --> 00:03:10.700
and those sorts of things.

00:03:10.700 --> 00:03:13.780
And then 97% of the time
was the heavy lifting,

00:03:13.780 --> 00:03:16.860
you know, the blocking,
tackling, and making

00:03:16.860 --> 00:03:19.490
that strategy happen.

00:03:19.490 --> 00:03:23.850
And initially, when I was
doing this for first few years,

00:03:23.850 --> 00:03:28.250
it was very exciting, because
you basically have a hypothesis

00:03:28.250 --> 00:03:31.590
and then you'd go out and try
to execute the hypotheses.

00:03:31.590 --> 00:03:35.030
And then you'd have
real-world results to look at.

00:03:35.030 --> 00:03:37.340
When I read Buffett's
biography, what dawned on me

00:03:37.340 --> 00:03:41.090
is that that 3% of time
that I was spending

00:03:41.090 --> 00:03:44.890
for someone like Warren
Buffett was like 80% of time,

00:03:44.890 --> 00:03:49.840
because what he was able to
do is apply the same analytics

00:03:49.840 --> 00:03:54.430
towards understanding
which businesses

00:03:54.430 --> 00:03:56.590
and industries and such
were great investments.

00:03:56.590 --> 00:03:59.380
And so the part of
the brain that you

00:03:59.380 --> 00:04:02.790
use in figuring out business
strategy and direction

00:04:02.790 --> 00:04:05.470
are pretty much almost
identical to the same parts

00:04:05.470 --> 00:04:07.650
that you would use
as an investor.

00:04:07.650 --> 00:04:11.750
And I always found
that the 3% of time

00:04:11.750 --> 00:04:14.950
were a lot more exciting
personally than the 97%.

00:04:14.950 --> 00:04:18.850
I mean, I enjoyed the 97%,
but nothing like the 3%.

00:04:18.850 --> 00:04:25.390
And so the idea of
blowing up the 3% to 80%

00:04:25.390 --> 00:04:29.130
by letting someone else in
effect run the business,

00:04:29.130 --> 00:04:31.270
and you figure
out where you want

00:04:31.270 --> 00:04:35.030
to allocate capital was
very exciting for me.

00:04:35.030 --> 00:04:41.120
And so that's what
led me to-- I had sold

00:04:41.120 --> 00:04:42.730
a few assets in the business.

00:04:42.730 --> 00:04:45.860
For the first time I
had about $1 million,

00:04:45.860 --> 00:04:47.480
which I didn't
have any need for.

00:04:47.480 --> 00:04:50.940
And so I decided to
take the $1 million

00:04:50.940 --> 00:04:55.120
and put it into
equity investments

00:04:55.120 --> 00:04:59.080
as an experiment to see how far
I could take Buffett's model

00:04:59.080 --> 00:05:02.390
and applying those same
analytics that I was using

00:05:02.390 --> 00:05:03.650
and I'd try to blow it up.

00:05:03.650 --> 00:05:06.720
So basically, I immediately
got to spend about 20 hours

00:05:06.720 --> 00:05:10.990
a week on what was normally
would have been just a week

00:05:10.990 --> 00:05:14.500
or two in a year and then a
lot of time just executing.

00:05:14.500 --> 00:05:16.590
And so if you can go
to the next slide.

00:05:16.590 --> 00:05:19.730
And so one of the
first investments

00:05:19.730 --> 00:05:22.880
I made-- this was in
'95-- and it actually

00:05:22.880 --> 00:05:25.170
show the interplay
between the real world,

00:05:25.170 --> 00:05:29.320
if you can call it that,
and the investing world.

00:05:29.320 --> 00:05:32.390
So I was running this
IT services company.

00:05:32.390 --> 00:05:34.850
There was this company in
India, which was called

00:05:34.850 --> 00:05:37.250
Satyam Computer Services.

00:05:37.250 --> 00:05:41.510
And Satyam was trying to expand
its business in the United

00:05:41.510 --> 00:05:42.570
States.

00:05:42.570 --> 00:05:46.610
And their sales team had
visited me in Chicago.

00:05:46.610 --> 00:05:49.660
They wanted to see is we could
do some kind of relationship.

00:05:49.660 --> 00:05:53.730
And we never did any business,
but I liked them a lot.

00:05:53.730 --> 00:05:56.680
I liked the people.

00:05:56.680 --> 00:05:59.260
And I liked the way they were
going about their business

00:05:59.260 --> 00:06:01.670
and how they were
positioning themselves.

00:06:01.670 --> 00:06:05.780
So then I decided to
study Satyam as a stock,

00:06:05.780 --> 00:06:09.300
because it was publicly
traded in India at the time.

00:06:09.300 --> 00:06:14.470
And when I studied it, I was
a novice investor at the time,

00:06:14.470 --> 00:06:18.860
but it blew my mind because
the market cap of Satyam

00:06:18.860 --> 00:06:22.180
was less than what
you might have valued

00:06:22.180 --> 00:06:23.880
their real estate in Hyderabad.

00:06:23.880 --> 00:06:28.150
So the stock was trading below
what would be just liquidation

00:06:28.150 --> 00:06:29.680
value on real estate.

00:06:29.680 --> 00:06:32.960
And this was a IT
services company

00:06:32.960 --> 00:06:37.070
that was growing something like
70% a year, very high margins.

00:06:37.070 --> 00:06:40.850
And I really couldn't see
the end of that runway.

00:06:40.850 --> 00:06:43.540
That runway was really big.

00:06:43.540 --> 00:06:48.210
And of course, investing in
India was really complicated,

00:06:48.210 --> 00:06:51.740
but I did it, but
I wasn't confident

00:06:51.740 --> 00:06:54.100
now because we didn't
have electronic trading.

00:06:54.100 --> 00:06:56.224
There were these flimsy
stocks that [INAUDIBLE].

00:06:56.224 --> 00:06:58.140
And I didn't fully trust
the Indian government

00:06:58.140 --> 00:07:00.106
on the ability to actually
get the money back

00:07:00.106 --> 00:07:01.480
in dollars, even
though they said

00:07:01.480 --> 00:07:02.604
the rules would allow that.

00:07:02.604 --> 00:07:07.240
So anyway, I made a $10,000
investment in Satyam.

00:07:07.240 --> 00:07:11.110
I bought three or
four different stocks.

00:07:11.110 --> 00:07:14.100
And Indian Satyam
was one of them.

00:07:14.100 --> 00:07:16.830
And I decided this is one of
those investments where you

00:07:16.830 --> 00:07:18.850
just buy and forget about it.

00:07:18.850 --> 00:07:23.010
Never look at it again and
just let it run for 10 years.

00:07:23.010 --> 00:07:27.094
And I bought it at
40 rupees a share.

00:07:27.094 --> 00:07:29.510
And about five years later--
and this you know, of course,

00:07:29.510 --> 00:07:35.260
we had the whole dot-com
boom in getting going--

00:07:35.260 --> 00:07:40.440
and Satyam had spun off
one of these dot coms.

00:07:40.440 --> 00:07:44.220
The stock had gone
from 40 rupees

00:07:44.220 --> 00:07:48.680
to in February or March
of 2007 7,000 rupees.

00:07:48.680 --> 00:07:52.660
So it had gone up
like 130-140 times.

00:07:52.660 --> 00:07:55.080
And currency had
moved again, we would

00:07:55.080 --> 00:07:57.190
have still even with
the currency moment

00:07:57.190 --> 00:07:58.810
it was more than 100x.

00:07:58.810 --> 00:08:02.970
And so I decided to stop
drinking the Kool Aid

00:08:02.970 --> 00:08:07.210
and do analysis of the
financials at that time,

00:08:07.210 --> 00:08:09.857
but I basically never
looked at it after that.

00:08:09.857 --> 00:08:12.190
And when I did the analysis,
it was creating at or north

00:08:12.190 --> 00:08:14.340
of 100 times earnings.

00:08:14.340 --> 00:08:18.450
And they had all these dot coms
which I couldn't figure out

00:08:18.450 --> 00:08:19.600
what they were worth.

00:08:19.600 --> 00:08:25.250
And I said, you know, I think
we've got more than a million

00:08:25.250 --> 00:08:26.747
in Satyam stock from the 10,000.

00:08:26.747 --> 00:08:29.080
And I think we're going to
take our money off the table.

00:08:29.080 --> 00:08:30.700
The other thing I
was concerned with I

00:08:30.700 --> 00:08:32.500
didn't know whether they
were allowed to put it back

00:08:32.500 --> 00:08:34.190
from India, because
the government said

00:08:34.190 --> 00:08:36.620
you could come in, give
us your foreign exchange,

00:08:36.620 --> 00:08:39.610
and when you sell it, no
long-term gain stocks,

00:08:39.610 --> 00:08:41.400
and you can pull the
whole thing back.

00:08:41.400 --> 00:08:42.530
And I didn't trust that.

00:08:42.530 --> 00:08:44.070
So I said let's test that.

00:08:44.070 --> 00:08:45.242
And so I sold.

00:08:45.242 --> 00:08:46.200
And didn't certificate.

00:08:46.200 --> 00:08:49.030
I didn't even know if
they were authentic.

00:08:49.030 --> 00:08:53.200
So it sold, and the money
got into my bank in India.

00:08:53.200 --> 00:08:55.650
And then I said wire it
to my bank in the US,

00:08:55.650 --> 00:08:57.250
and the next day
it was in the US.

00:08:57.250 --> 00:09:00.429
OK, so the whole thing
actually worked exactly

00:09:00.429 --> 00:09:01.220
they said it would.

00:09:01.220 --> 00:09:02.750
Then I said, well,
you know, I should've

00:09:02.750 --> 00:09:04.000
trusted them a little bit more.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:04.791
So that was Satyam.

00:09:04.791 --> 00:09:06.050
We can go to the next slide.

00:09:06.050 --> 00:09:08.930
And so there was
this other company

00:09:08.930 --> 00:09:12.250
in the mid '90s PeopleSoft.

00:09:12.250 --> 00:09:14.470
And one of the things
were the interplay

00:09:14.470 --> 00:09:18.070
between investing and
running a business,

00:09:18.070 --> 00:09:21.420
so we were basically
doing system integration.

00:09:21.420 --> 00:09:25.020
So for example, we
had a team which

00:09:25.020 --> 00:09:27.330
had expertise in
Sybase and Oracle, all

00:09:27.330 --> 00:09:28.720
these different databases.

00:09:28.720 --> 00:09:32.230
And what I started doing when
I was looking at investing,

00:09:32.230 --> 00:09:34.230
I started looking at all
the software companies,

00:09:34.230 --> 00:09:36.130
because that was an
area I understood.

00:09:36.130 --> 00:09:41.310
And one of the companies I
found with a very high P/E ratio

00:09:41.310 --> 00:09:42.122
was PeopleSoft.

00:09:42.122 --> 00:09:44.580
I think it was creating nearly
more than 50 times earnings.

00:09:44.580 --> 00:09:46.920
And PeopleSoft was
like SAP, basically,

00:09:46.920 --> 00:09:49.260
where they needed
system integrators

00:09:49.260 --> 00:09:51.166
to go in and
implement the product.

00:09:51.166 --> 00:09:52.540
So I said, well,
you know, what I

00:09:52.540 --> 00:09:55.670
can do is I can't buy the
stock, because it's ridiculously

00:09:55.670 --> 00:09:58.760
priced, but I can
do a back door.

00:09:58.760 --> 00:10:01.740
And the back door I
did, I said, well,

00:10:01.740 --> 00:10:04.160
the market is mostly efficient.

00:10:04.160 --> 00:10:06.850
So if it's a 50 times
earnings, the market

00:10:06.850 --> 00:10:10.570
expects tremendous growth.

00:10:10.570 --> 00:10:12.810
And it looked to me like
it would grow a lot.

00:10:12.810 --> 00:10:16.180
So I said if we and
my company, TransTech,

00:10:16.180 --> 00:10:19.990
set up a PeopleSoft
practice, that would not

00:10:19.990 --> 00:10:21.960
be buying at 50 times earnings.

00:10:21.960 --> 00:10:25.410
I would just be hiring people.

00:10:25.410 --> 00:10:28.160
And then I'd have them build out
of these different companies.

00:10:28.160 --> 00:10:30.580
And it would be pretty
spectacular margins

00:10:30.580 --> 00:10:33.440
because it was so
new and growing.

00:10:33.440 --> 00:10:37.760
So I decided we would set
up a PeopleSoft practice.

00:10:37.760 --> 00:10:41.070
And I still remember the
economics were just incredible

00:10:41.070 --> 00:10:46.061
because I hired this guy who was
probably the most expensive guy

00:10:46.061 --> 00:10:47.310
we'd ever hired at that times.

00:10:47.310 --> 00:10:49.320
This was '96 or
something, I think.

00:10:49.320 --> 00:10:52.040
He was a PeopleSoft
practice leader.

00:10:52.040 --> 00:10:55.740
And I think he cost us maybe
quarter million a year.

00:10:55.740 --> 00:11:01.390
And when we hired him, we didn't
know what we would do with him.

00:11:01.390 --> 00:11:04.199
But I just said, OK, I need to
have some horsepower coming in,

00:11:04.199 --> 00:11:06.240
so we can then figure out,
because this guy knows

00:11:06.240 --> 00:11:06.720
what he's doing.

00:11:06.720 --> 00:11:09.400
I said, once he comes in, then
we'll sit down and figure out

00:11:09.400 --> 00:11:09.900
what to do.

00:11:09.900 --> 00:11:15.060
So he comes in to work the first
day and he says, by the way,

00:11:15.060 --> 00:11:16.830
are you looking for clients?

00:11:16.830 --> 00:11:18.530
I said, yeah, we're
looking for clients.

00:11:18.530 --> 00:11:22.909
And he said, well, you know,
I've got these relationships,

00:11:22.909 --> 00:11:24.200
there are three or four places.

00:11:24.200 --> 00:11:27.900
And I can go in with
a team of 15 people.

00:11:27.900 --> 00:11:31.499
So I said, Paul, I don't
have the 15 people.

00:11:31.499 --> 00:11:32.290
Do know the people?

00:11:32.290 --> 00:11:34.060
He said, yeah, I
know the people too.

00:11:34.060 --> 00:11:39.580
OK, so he helped us hire
these 15 buddies of his.

00:11:39.580 --> 00:11:46.540
And I don't think it was even
a day that he was non-billable.

00:11:46.540 --> 00:11:51.860
So in two days he's building
at multiples of the quarter

00:11:51.860 --> 00:11:54.270
million that I'm paying him.

00:11:54.270 --> 00:11:57.350
And the team is going
in at 50% margins

00:11:57.350 --> 00:11:59.290
after covering all expenses.

00:11:59.290 --> 00:12:03.190
And so when I looked at what
happened with PeopleSoft,

00:12:03.190 --> 00:12:05.200
our actual cash out
the door-- we're

00:12:05.200 --> 00:12:10.050
kind of be like the Dell
model, where you ship the PC

00:12:10.050 --> 00:12:11.830
and then you pay
your suppliers later.

00:12:11.830 --> 00:12:14.850
I hadn't even paid the
payroll on these people

00:12:14.850 --> 00:12:16.890
before we raised
our first invoice.

00:12:16.890 --> 00:12:18.404
And the invoice was
at a huge margin

00:12:18.404 --> 00:12:19.820
to what we were
going to pay them.

00:12:19.820 --> 00:12:22.580
So when I actually
calculated dollars

00:12:22.580 --> 00:12:24.080
invested in the
PeopleSoft practice,

00:12:24.080 --> 00:12:26.250
I think it was a
negative number.

00:12:26.250 --> 00:12:30.780
And in the end, a lot of
the rest of our IT business

00:12:30.780 --> 00:12:34.220
was kind of declining
because it was matured out

00:12:34.220 --> 00:12:35.810
and getting competitive.

00:12:35.810 --> 00:12:38.000
This was very high margin.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:39.450
And so that's an
example of how I

00:12:39.450 --> 00:12:45.400
used the stock market to drive--
I said, no, this is cool.

00:12:45.400 --> 00:12:48.320
I'll just keep looking at
companies that have 50, 60, 70,

00:12:48.320 --> 00:12:50.784
100 times earnings and
then go build a practice.

00:12:50.784 --> 00:12:52.200
And I know they're
going to go up.

00:12:52.200 --> 00:12:53.491
And so that worked really well.

00:12:53.491 --> 00:12:55.140
So we go to the next slide.

00:12:55.140 --> 00:13:05.330
And so we had Satyam and
stuff, which from '95 to '99,

00:13:05.330 --> 00:13:09.561
I think, I'd done like north of
70% a year on that $1 million

00:13:09.561 --> 00:13:10.310
we originally had.

00:13:10.310 --> 00:13:12.370
So things had gone really well.

00:13:12.370 --> 00:13:17.771
But then in '99, and this was
when Pabrai Funds had started,

00:13:17.771 --> 00:13:19.270
one of the first
investments we made

00:13:19.270 --> 00:13:26.800
is I was seeing the big
bubble in the internet.

00:13:26.800 --> 00:13:31.360
And it was clear to me that the
internet was transformational.

00:13:31.360 --> 00:13:36.420
But also I was very skeptical
of the pets.coms, if you will.

00:13:36.420 --> 00:13:38.780
