00:31:40.300 --> 00:31:43.950
The question is simply what
was the most unexpected

00:31:43.950 --> 00:31:48.240
surprising thing
that you guys felt

00:31:48.240 --> 00:31:52.234
when you met with Warren Buffett
during your lunch with him?

00:31:52.234 --> 00:31:53.900
MOHNISH PABRAI: Do
you want to go first?

00:31:56.430 --> 00:31:59.070
GUY SPIER: You know, one
of the things that really

00:31:59.070 --> 00:32:02.242
got to me at the
time was when I asked

00:32:02.242 --> 00:32:03.450
him this question about envy.

00:32:06.610 --> 00:32:09.060
I had the courage
to ask about myself.

00:32:09.060 --> 00:32:12.010
So the question that
I asked him was,

00:32:12.010 --> 00:32:15.140
Warren, imagine I'm one of your
managers of your businesses,

00:32:15.140 --> 00:32:16.890
an important business
that generates

00:32:16.890 --> 00:32:20.955
a lot of cash for your office.

00:32:20.955 --> 00:32:23.080
And imagine that I come to
you and I say, you know,

00:32:23.080 --> 00:32:26.660
I'm sort of grips with envy of
other people in my industry.

00:32:26.660 --> 00:32:29.460
And it's affecting
my performance.

00:32:29.460 --> 00:32:32.280
And I expected Warren
to come back to me

00:32:32.280 --> 00:32:34.260
with some brilliant answer.

00:32:34.260 --> 00:32:36.246
And he just looked at me.

00:32:36.246 --> 00:32:37.620
And I said, so
what would you do?

00:32:37.620 --> 00:32:42.170
And he just looked at me
and went, I don't know.

00:32:42.170 --> 00:32:45.050
I was both a little sort of
shocked and disappointed,

00:32:45.050 --> 00:32:47.740
because I was
expecting some wisdom.

00:32:47.740 --> 00:32:49.350
And I think what
that did to me is

00:32:49.350 --> 00:32:52.550
it made me struggle
with that afterwards

00:32:52.550 --> 00:32:57.060
and forced me to come
up with my own answers.

00:32:57.060 --> 00:33:00.110
And I think it's a
testament to Warren Buffett

00:33:00.110 --> 00:33:03.180
that he is so
congruent and aligned.

00:33:03.180 --> 00:33:05.640
I think that when you're
congruent and aligned

00:33:05.640 --> 00:33:07.480
with yourself, when
you love what you do,

00:33:07.480 --> 00:33:09.970
you don't get envious
of other people,

00:33:09.970 --> 00:33:11.830
because you're happy
for them to be happy.

00:33:11.830 --> 00:33:12.750
And you love what you do.

00:33:12.750 --> 00:33:14.416
If Mohnish is playing
bridge, he doesn't

00:33:14.416 --> 00:33:17.510
care that some other guy is
driving a Formula One racing

00:33:17.510 --> 00:33:18.130
car.

00:33:18.130 --> 00:33:20.250
And because Warren has
been so aligned for so long

00:33:20.250 --> 00:33:22.720
the thought was just
utter anathema to him.

00:33:22.720 --> 00:33:26.200
And I think it made me
realize that the answer was

00:33:26.200 --> 00:33:30.070
to drop all these things I
was doing, that was trying,

00:33:30.070 --> 00:33:32.840
in which I was
misaligned, basically.

00:33:32.840 --> 00:33:35.237
It's actually one
of the great clues

00:33:35.237 --> 00:33:37.320
that you're misaligned is
that you're feeling envy

00:33:37.320 --> 00:33:39.870
with something else.

00:33:39.870 --> 00:33:43.060
Emotions are a call to action.

00:33:43.060 --> 00:33:46.594
And the emotion of envy says
there's something in my life

00:33:46.594 --> 00:33:47.510
that I need to change.

00:33:47.510 --> 00:33:49.520
And if you direct
yourself inwards, which I

00:33:49.520 --> 00:33:51.650
by some miracle managed to do.

00:33:51.650 --> 00:33:54.080
There's one of the
many surprising things.

00:33:54.080 --> 00:33:55.301
SAURABH MADAAN: Thank you.

00:33:55.301 --> 00:33:55.800
Mohnish?

00:33:55.800 --> 00:33:59.680
GUY SPIER: What I found, what
I've found very surprising

00:33:59.680 --> 00:34:03.950
was that Warren's
got plenty going On.

00:34:03.950 --> 00:34:06.610
He's got more than
300,000 employees.

00:34:06.610 --> 00:34:07.360
Huge company.

00:34:07.360 --> 00:34:11.409
Obviously, he agreed to have
lunch as a charity lunch.

00:34:11.409 --> 00:34:14.620
But the thing that surprised
me is that he truly showed up.

00:34:14.620 --> 00:34:18.340
So his perspective when
he came for the lunch was

00:34:18.340 --> 00:34:22.060
that these people who I don't
know very well, don't know

00:34:22.060 --> 00:34:25.929
or at all, really, for
them, this is a big deal.

00:34:25.929 --> 00:34:28.239
He understood that really well.

00:34:28.239 --> 00:34:34.840
And he understood that he
was there to deliver value.

00:34:34.840 --> 00:34:39.270
And so he wanted to
make sure that we

00:34:39.270 --> 00:34:41.179
felt like we got a bargain.

00:34:41.179 --> 00:34:45.230
And so whenever we
asked a question,

00:34:45.230 --> 00:34:49.449
he converted the question
into a learning opportunity.

00:34:49.449 --> 00:34:51.199
And so I would just
ask him a question,

00:34:51.199 --> 00:34:54.050
like, for example,
hey, Warren, there

00:34:54.050 --> 00:34:58.670
was this third kind of pseudo
partner of Rick Guerin.

00:34:58.670 --> 00:35:01.762
And then after the '70s, he
kind of dropped off the radar.

00:35:01.762 --> 00:35:02.970
What happened to Rick Guerin?

00:35:02.970 --> 00:35:05.540
And he took that
opportunity to give us

00:35:05.540 --> 00:35:10.630
a lesson on leverage and
different things, which

00:35:10.630 --> 00:35:13.310
was very powerful.

00:35:13.310 --> 00:35:15.330
And the other thing
I would say is

00:35:15.330 --> 00:35:22.840
that in meeting him and
meeting Charlie Munger,

00:35:22.840 --> 00:35:26.870
both these individuals are
off-the-chart brilliant.

00:35:26.870 --> 00:35:30.550
I would say that they are
unworldly brilliant, because I

00:35:30.550 --> 00:35:34.500
asked him questions that
I know he would have never

00:35:34.500 --> 00:35:37.750
had any talk that I
want to ask and had

00:35:37.750 --> 00:35:40.330
any prior of processing.

00:35:40.330 --> 00:35:43.380
But the way the answers came
out, and especially, many times

00:35:43.380 --> 00:35:46.010
that I've done that for Charlie
Munger with these extremely

00:35:46.010 --> 00:35:52.500
left-field questions, I would
say this that I have never

00:35:52.500 --> 00:35:56.470
ever met a person
who is anywhere

00:35:56.470 --> 00:35:58.900
close to the brilliance
of Charlie Munger.

00:35:58.900 --> 00:36:01.220
I would say he
surpasses Warren-- sorry

00:36:01.220 --> 00:36:05.590
Warren-- he surpasses Warren
by quite some distance.

00:36:05.590 --> 00:36:09.230
And Warren himself
surpasses most of humanity

00:36:09.230 --> 00:36:10.852
by quite some distance.

00:36:10.852 --> 00:36:12.560
So that was the thing
that a lot of thing

00:36:12.560 --> 00:36:14.810
was you could just
see that there is just

00:36:14.810 --> 00:36:17.815
horsepower coming out of their
ears, incredible horsepower.

00:36:17.815 --> 00:36:19.440
And they get output
out of that engine.

00:36:19.440 --> 00:36:22.160
A lot of people have horsepower,
they don't get output.

00:36:22.160 --> 00:36:27.140
These are Formula One Ferraris,
which are delivering output.

00:36:27.140 --> 00:36:29.100
GUY SPIER: Sorry,
just to riff on that.

00:36:29.100 --> 00:36:33.370
If we get asked, I get asked
all the time was it worth it.

00:36:33.370 --> 00:36:35.920
And I can't tell
you the feeding.

00:36:35.920 --> 00:36:39.314
So somebody, here's the
richest man on the planet

00:36:39.314 --> 00:36:41.480
or maybe he's the second
greatest, I don't remember.

00:36:41.480 --> 00:36:47.560
And he's determined to deliver
extreme amounts of value

00:36:47.560 --> 00:36:51.440
to complete yo-yos, and
their wives, and children.

00:36:51.440 --> 00:36:55.130
And that almost makes you
want to jump out of your seat.

00:36:55.130 --> 00:36:56.330
It's not what you expect.

00:36:56.330 --> 00:36:58.300
And here's what I've learned.

00:36:58.300 --> 00:37:00.580
If Warren Buffett was
doing that for us,

00:37:00.580 --> 00:37:02.870
you can be sure that he does
that for every single one

00:37:02.870 --> 00:37:03.953
of the Berkshire managers.

00:37:03.953 --> 00:37:06.090
He does it for many,
many other people.

00:37:06.090 --> 00:37:08.230
And it made me
realize if you have

00:37:08.230 --> 00:37:10.960
the sense that the richest
on the planet, most

00:37:10.960 --> 00:37:13.660
successful businessman,
most successful investor,

00:37:13.660 --> 00:37:15.620
he would not feel obliged to do.

00:37:15.620 --> 00:37:18.870
He'd feel like his
presence is sufficient.

00:37:18.870 --> 00:37:20.810
There's no other way,
I think, to really

00:37:20.810 --> 00:37:23.450
have learned the
insight that we really

00:37:23.450 --> 00:37:25.300
are here to serve other people.

00:37:25.300 --> 00:37:28.460
And we get success in life when
we take that very seriously

00:37:28.460 --> 00:37:31.100
and we deliver with
enthusiasm value,

00:37:31.100 --> 00:37:35.090
even two yo-yos who've
showed up for charity lunch.

00:37:35.090 --> 00:37:38.450
But I would even argue that so
we're at the end of the lunch,

00:37:38.450 --> 00:37:41.291
and, of course, where our
attention is totally focused

00:37:41.291 --> 00:37:41.790
on him.

00:37:41.790 --> 00:37:44.446
There are many other things that
we would like to do and ask.

00:37:44.446 --> 00:37:45.570
And he says, wait a second.

00:37:45.570 --> 00:37:47.403
Let we just take care
of these waiters here.

00:37:47.403 --> 00:37:49.790
He went and personally
tipped at least one or more

00:37:49.790 --> 00:37:51.010
of the waiters.

00:37:51.010 --> 00:37:52.940
So it wasn't just for us.

00:37:52.940 --> 00:37:55.269
It was for everybody who
made the occasion possible.

00:37:55.269 --> 00:37:56.810
I don't think there's
any way I could

00:37:56.810 --> 00:37:59.920
have learned that lesson,
other than being at a lunch

00:37:59.920 --> 00:38:01.641
like that.

